The US president has authorised up to $200 million in military equipment to Ukraine, as the country’s officials have pleaded for more help to defend against heavy shelling by Russian forces. This brings the total of US security aid provided to Ukraine to $1.2 billion since January 2021, according to senior administration officials. In a memorandum to Secretary of State Antony Blinken, Joe Biden authorised the up to $200 million (£150m) in additional security assistance, the White House said, paving the way for the “immediate” shipment of fresh military equipment to Ukraine. UN Chief Seeks End To Syria War France To Offer Fuel Rebate To Help Motorists The funds can be used for weapons and other articles from the US Defence Department’s stock, as well as military education and training to help Ukraine against the Russian invasion, now in its third week. One official said: “It will provide immediate military assistance to Ukraine, including anti-armour, anti-aircraft systems, and small arms in support of Ukraine’s front-line defenders.” The Pentagon declined to comment, according to Reuters. Ukraine has been asking for more Javelin anti-tank weapons and Stinger missiles to shoot down aircraft. It’s foreign minister, Dmytro Kuleba, on Saturday underscored Ukraine’s need for additional military supplies in an interview with the non-profit Renew Democracy Initiative. POLL The United States has drawn from its weapons stocks to supply Ukraine, beginning in the autumn of 2021 and then again in December and February. The last batch of weapons provided in February included anti-armour, small arms, body armour and various munitions, according to the Pentagon, as well as anti-aircraft systems. On Thursday, the US Congress approved $13.6 billion in emergency aid for Ukraine.